digraph RetroQuestReturns {
	graph [
		goal="Build RetroQuest Returns: a modern retrospective board web app using Go (stdlib), htmx + Tailwind CSS, and PostgreSQL. Tier 1 features: team create/login, 3 default columns, thoughts CRUD with unlimited voting, action items CRUD with completion and assignee, end retro/archive, SSE real-time updates, responsive layout."
	]
	rankdir=LR

	start [shape=Mdiamond, label="Start"]
	exit  [shape=Msquare, label="Exit"]

	analyze [
		shape=box,
		label="Analyze Old Codebase",
		model="anthropic/claude-opus-4.6",
		max_retries=1,
		prompt="You are analyzing a deprecated web application called RetroQuest to produce a feature specification for its replacement. The old codebase is at deprecated-retroquest/retroquest/ in your working directory.

Study these areas of the old codebase:
1. Backend API structure: read files in deprecated-retroquest/retroquest/api/src/main/java/com/ford/labs/retroquest/ -- look at the controller, service, and entity classes for: team, board, column, thought, actionitem
2. Frontend structure: read deprecated-retroquest/retroquest/ui/src/App/Team/Retro/ for the retro board components, and ui/src/App/ for page structure
3. Database schema: read deprecated-retroquest/retroquest/api/src/main/resources/db/changelog.xml for table definitions

Based on your analysis, write a file called FEATURE_SPEC.md that defines the Tier 1 feature set for the new application:

- Team management: create team (name + password), login with team name + password, no individual user accounts
- Retro board: 3 default columns (Happy, Sad, Action Items) created when a team is created
- Thoughts: create, edit, delete thoughts in Happy and Sad columns. Unlimited voting (increment a counter, no per-user tracking). Mark as discussed.
- Action items: create, edit, delete. Fields: task text, assignee (free text), completed (boolean). Display in the Action Items column.
- End retro / archive: archive the current board (thoughts become read-only historical records), action items carry forward unless completed
- Real-time: all connected clients see changes immediately via Server-Sent Events (SSE)
- Responsive layout: works on desktop and mobile

For each feature, document: what it does, the user interaction flow, and any important business rules from the old code. Keep it concise and actionable -- this document will be the input to the design stage.

Tech stack for the new version (do NOT implement yet, just note in the spec):
- Backend: Go, standard library only (net/http), no frameworks
- Frontend: HTML templates rendered server-side, htmx for dynamic interactions, Tailwind CSS for styling
- Database: PostgreSQL via pgx driver
- Real-time: SSE + Postgres LISTEN/NOTIFY
- Architecture: monolith (single Go binary)"
	]

	design [
		shape=box,
		label="Design Architecture",
		model="anthropic/claude-opus-4.6",
		max_retries=1,
		prompt="You are designing the architecture for RetroQuest Returns. Read FEATURE_SPEC.md for the complete feature specification.

Write a file called DESIGN.md that covers ALL of the following sections:

1. PROJECT STRUCTURE
   Define the Go project layout:
   cmd/server/main.go -- entry point
   internal/server/ -- HTTP server setup, routing, middleware
   internal/models/ -- domain types (Team, Board, Column, Thought, ActionItem)
   internal/db/ -- database connection, queries, migrations
   internal/handlers/ -- HTTP handler functions grouped by domain
   internal/sse/ -- SSE hub and broadcast logic
   internal/auth/ -- team authentication (session/cookie based)
   templates/ -- Go HTML templates (base layout + page templates)
   static/ -- CSS, JS (htmx, Tailwind via CDN)
   migrations/ -- SQL migration files (numbered: 001_create_tables.sql, etc.)

2. DATABASE SCHEMA
   Define every table with columns, types, constraints, and indexes:
   - teams: id (UUID PK), name (TEXT UNIQUE NOT NULL), password_hash (TEXT NOT NULL), created_at
   - boards: id (UUID PK), team_id (UUID FK NOT NULL), created_at, archived (BOOLEAN DEFAULT false)
   - columns: id (UUID PK), team_id (UUID FK NOT NULL), title (TEXT NOT NULL), sort_order (INT), created_at
   - thoughts: id (UUID PK), board_id (UUID FK NOT NULL), column_id (UUID FK NOT NULL), message (TEXT NOT NULL), hearts (INT DEFAULT 0), discussed (BOOLEAN DEFAULT false), created_at
   - action_items: id (UUID PK), team_id (UUID FK NOT NULL), task (TEXT NOT NULL), assignee (TEXT DEFAULT ''), completed (BOOLEAN DEFAULT false), archived (BOOLEAN DEFAULT false), created_at

3. HTTP API ROUTES
   List every route with method, path, handler function, request/response:
   POST /api/teams -- create team
   POST /api/teams/login -- login
   GET / -- redirect to /login
   GET /login -- login page
   GET /create -- create team page
   GET /team/{teamId} -- retro board page (requires auth)
   POST /team/{teamId}/thoughts -- create thought (htmx)
   PUT /team/{teamId}/thoughts/{id} -- update thought
   DELETE /team/{teamId}/thoughts/{id} -- delete thought
   POST /team/{teamId}/thoughts/{id}/heart -- increment heart count
   POST /team/{teamId}/thoughts/{id}/discuss -- toggle discussed
   POST /team/{teamId}/action-items -- create action item
   PUT /team/{teamId}/action-items/{id} -- update action item
   DELETE /team/{teamId}/action-items/{id} -- delete action item
   POST /team/{teamId}/action-items/{id}/complete -- toggle completed
   POST /team/{teamId}/end-retro -- archive current board, create new one
   GET /team/{teamId}/archives -- archives page
   GET /team/{teamId}/events -- SSE endpoint

4. TEMPLATE STRUCTURE
   List all HTML templates and what they render:
   templates/base.html -- layout with head (Tailwind CDN, htmx CDN), nav, content block
   templates/login.html -- login form
   templates/create.html -- create team form
   templates/retro.html -- main retro board with 3 columns
   templates/partials/thought.html -- single thought card (for htmx swap)
   templates/partials/thought_form.html -- thought input form
   templates/partials/action_item.html -- single action item row
   templates/partials/action_item_form.html -- action item input form
   templates/partials/column.html -- column container with thoughts
   templates/archives.html -- archived boards list

5. SSE EVENT DESIGN
   Define event types and payloads:
   thought-created, thought-updated, thought-deleted, thought-hearted, thought-discussed
   action-item-created, action-item-updated, action-item-deleted, action-item-completed
   board-archived
   Use Postgres LISTEN/NOTIFY on channel 'retro_events' with JSON payload containing event type, team_id, and entity data.

6. AUTHENTICATION
   Cookie-based team sessions. On login, set a signed cookie with team_id. Middleware checks cookie on /team/* routes. No individual users.

Be precise and complete. This document is the blueprint for implementation."
	]

	scaffold [
		shape=box,
		label="Scaffold Project",
		model="anthropic/claude-opus-4.6",
		max_retries=1,
		prompt="You are setting up the project skeleton for RetroQuest Returns. Read DESIGN.md for the full architecture.

Create the following files and directories:

1. go.mod -- module github.com/campallison/retroquest-returns, Go 1.21+
2. cmd/server/main.go -- main entry point that:
   - Loads .env file for DATABASE_URL and PORT
   - Connects to PostgreSQL
   - Runs SQL migrations from migrations/ directory
   - Sets up the HTTP router with all routes from DESIGN.md (handler functions can be stubs that return 501)
   - Starts the server on PORT (default 8080)
3. internal/server/server.go -- NewServer function, route registration
4. internal/models/models.go -- all domain struct types from DESIGN.md
5. internal/db/db.go -- database connection helper (pgx pool)
6. internal/db/migrate.go -- simple migration runner (reads .sql files from migrations/ in order)
7. internal/handlers/ -- create handler files with stub functions for each route group:
   - team.go, thought.go, action_item.go, board.go, sse.go
8. internal/auth/auth.go -- cookie helpers (stub)
9. internal/sse/hub.go -- SSE hub struct (stub)
10. templates/base.html -- base layout with Tailwind CSS CDN and htmx CDN in head, basic nav
11. static/ -- empty directory (create a .gitkeep)
12. migrations/001_create_tables.sql -- full schema DDL from DESIGN.md
13. docker-compose.yml -- Postgres service (postgres:16, port 5432, retroquest db)
14. Update .env.example with DATABASE_URL=postgres://postgres:postgres@localhost:5432/retroquest?sslmode=disable and PORT=8080

Use the pgx/v5 driver (github.com/jackc/pgx/v5). After creating all files, run 'go mod tidy' via the shell tool if possible (it may not work in the sandbox, that is OK).

The project should have a valid structure that a Go developer could navigate. Handler stubs should have the correct function signatures matching the router setup even though they return 501."
	]

	backend [
		shape=box,
		label="Implement Backend",
		model="anthropic/claude-opus-4.6",
		max_retries=1,
		prompt="You are implementing the full backend for RetroQuest Returns. Read DESIGN.md for the architecture and then read the existing scaffold code to understand the project structure.

Start by reading these files to understand what exists:
- DESIGN.md
- cmd/server/main.go
- internal/server/server.go
- internal/models/models.go
- internal/db/db.go
- internal/handlers/ (all files)

Then implement ALL of the following, replacing stubs with working code:

1. DATABASE LAYER (internal/db/)
   - db.go: connection pool setup using pgx/v5/pgxpool
   - migrate.go: read and execute .sql files from migrations/ directory in sorted order
   - queries.go (new): all SQL query functions:
     * CreateTeam, GetTeamByName, GetTeamByID
     * CreateBoard, GetActiveBoard, GetArchivedBoards, ArchiveBoard
     * GetColumnsByTeam, CreateDefaultColumns
     * CreateThought, UpdateThought, DeleteThought, GetThoughtsByBoard, IncrementHearts, ToggleDiscussed
     * CreateActionItem, UpdateActionItem, DeleteActionItem, GetActionItemsByTeam, ToggleCompleted, ArchiveCompletedActionItems
   - Use parameterized queries everywhere (never string concatenation for SQL)

2. AUTHENTICATION (internal/auth/)
   - Sign and verify team session cookies using HMAC-SHA256
   - Login handler: verify password with bcrypt
   - Middleware: extract team_id from cookie, reject if missing/invalid
   - Use a JWT_SECRET or COOKIE_SECRET from environment

3. HANDLERS (internal/handlers/)
   - team.go: CreateTeam (POST, hash password with bcrypt, create team + default board + 3 columns), Login (POST, verify password, set cookie), LoginPage (GET, render template), CreateTeamPage (GET, render template)
   - thought.go: CreateThought (POST, insert + notify), UpdateThought (PUT), DeleteThought (DELETE), HeartThought (POST, increment + notify), DiscussThought (POST, toggle + notify). Return htmx partials.
   - action_item.go: CreateActionItem (POST + notify), UpdateActionItem (PUT + notify), DeleteActionItem (DELETE + notify), ToggleCompleted (POST + notify). Return htmx partials.
   - board.go: RetroPage (GET, render full board), EndRetro (POST, archive board + create new one + notify), ArchivesPage (GET, render archives)
   - sse.go: SSE endpoint handler, integrate with SSE hub

4. SSE (internal/sse/)
   - Hub: manage connected clients per team, broadcast events
   - Postgres LISTEN/NOTIFY: listen on 'retro_events' channel, parse JSON payload, route to correct team's clients
   - Event format: 'event: <type>\ndata: <html_partial>\n\n'
   - The SSE handler should use htmx SSE extension format

5. SERVER WIRING (internal/server/ and cmd/server/main.go)
   - Wire all handlers with database pool and SSE hub
   - Add auth middleware to /team/* routes
   - Serve static files from static/
   - Parse templates at startup

Make sure all handlers that modify data also send a Postgres NOTIFY so SSE clients get updates. Use the pattern: after a successful DB write, call pg_notify('retro_events', json_payload)."
	]

	frontend [
		shape=box,
		label="Implement Frontend",
		model="anthropic/claude-opus-4.6",
		max_retries=1,
		prompt="You are implementing the frontend for RetroQuest Returns. Read DESIGN.md for the template structure, then read the backend handler code to understand what routes exist and what data they pass to templates.

Start by reading:
- DESIGN.md (section 4: Template Structure)
- internal/handlers/ (all files, to see what template data each handler provides)
- templates/base.html (the existing scaffold)

Then implement ALL templates with htmx and Tailwind CSS:

1. templates/base.html -- Complete the base layout:
   - Include Tailwind CSS via CDN (https://cdn.tailwindcss.com)
   - Include htmx via CDN (https://unpkg.com/htmx.org@2.0.4)
   - Include htmx SSE extension (https://unpkg.com/htmx-ext-sse@2.3.0/sse.js)
   - Responsive nav bar with app name, team name (when logged in), logout link
   - Content block for page-specific content
   - Use a clean, modern color scheme (e.g., indigo/slate)

2. templates/login.html -- Login page:
   - Form: team name input, password input, submit button
   - POST to /api/teams/login, redirect to /team/{teamId} on success
   - Link to create team page
   - Centered card layout, mobile-friendly

3. templates/create.html -- Create team page:
   - Form: team name, password, confirm password
   - POST to /api/teams, redirect to team page on success
   - Link back to login
   - Client-side password match validation

4. templates/retro.html -- Main retro board (the core page):
   - Connect to SSE endpoint using hx-ext='sse' and sse-connect='/team/{teamId}/events'
   - 3-column layout (responsive: side-by-side on desktop, stacked on mobile)
   - Each column header shows column title
   - Happy and Sad columns: list of thought cards + input form at top
   - Action Items column: list of action items + input form at top
   - End Retro button in header area
   - Use sse-swap for real-time updates targeting specific element IDs

5. templates/partials/thought.html -- Single thought card:
   - Display message text
   - Heart button with count (hx-post to heart endpoint, hx-swap='outerHTML')
   - Discussed toggle (hx-post, visual indicator like strikethrough or dimming)
   - Edit button (switches to inline edit form)
   - Delete button (hx-delete, hx-swap='outerHTML' with empty response or hx-target closest with delete swap)
   - Style: card with shadow, padding, rounded corners

6. templates/partials/thought_form.html -- Thought input:
   - Text input + submit button
   - hx-post to create thought endpoint
   - hx-target the thought list container, hx-swap='beforeend'
   - Clear form after submit

7. templates/partials/action_item.html -- Action item row:
   - Checkbox for completed (hx-post to toggle)
   - Task text (editable inline)
   - Assignee field (editable inline)
   - Delete button
   - Completed items should have visual distinction (strikethrough, muted color)

8. templates/partials/action_item_form.html -- Action item input:
   - Task text input + assignee input + submit button
   - hx-post to create endpoint

9. templates/archives.html -- Archives page:
   - List of archived boards with dates
   - Each board expandable to show its thoughts (read-only)
   - Link back to current retro

Make all templates responsive using Tailwind breakpoints (sm, md, lg). Use a consistent visual design: clean cards, clear typography, good spacing. The retro board should feel pleasant to use."
	]

	tests [
		shape=box,
		label="Write Tests",
		model="anthropic/claude-opus-4.6",
		max_retries=1,
		prompt="You are writing comprehensive tests for the RetroQuest Returns application. Read the entire codebase first to understand what has been implemented.

Start by reading:
- DESIGN.md (for the architecture and expected behavior)
- internal/models/models.go (domain types)
- internal/db/ (all files -- connection, queries)
- internal/auth/auth.go (cookie signing, middleware)
- internal/handlers/ (all files)
- internal/sse/hub.go (SSE hub)
- cmd/server/main.go and internal/server/server.go (wiring)

TESTING CONVENTIONS -- follow these strictly:

1. Use TABLE-DRIVEN TESTS as the preferred pattern. Each test function should define a slice of test cases with name, inputs, and expected outputs, then loop over them with t.Run(tc.name, ...).

2. Use github.com/google/go-cmp/cmp for ALL assertions. Import it as: import \"github.com/google/go-cmp/cmp\"
   - For equality checks: if diff := cmp.Diff(want, got); diff != \"\" { t.Errorf(\"mismatch (-want +got):\\n%s\", diff) }
   - Do NOT use reflect.DeepEqual or manual field-by-field comparisons.
   - Run 'go get github.com/google/go-cmp/cmp' via the shell tool to add the dependency.

3. Place test files next to the code they test (e.g., internal/auth/auth_test.go).

TESTS TO WRITE:

1. internal/auth/auth_test.go -- Unit tests for authentication:
   - TestSignCookie / TestVerifyCookie: table-driven, test valid signatures, tampered values, expired cookies, empty input
   - TestAuthMiddleware: test that protected routes reject unauthenticated requests and pass authenticated ones through

2. internal/handlers/team_test.go -- Unit tests for team handlers:
   - Use httptest.NewRequest and httptest.NewRecorder
   - Define a DB interface or use the concrete query functions with a mock
   - TestCreateTeamHandler: valid creation, duplicate name, missing fields, password hashing verification
   - TestLoginHandler: valid login, wrong password, non-existent team

3. internal/handlers/thought_test.go -- Unit tests for thought handlers:
   - TestCreateThoughtHandler: valid creation, empty message, missing column_id
   - TestHeartThoughtHandler: verify heart count increments
   - TestDeleteThoughtHandler: valid deletion, non-existent thought

4. internal/handlers/action_item_test.go -- Unit tests for action item handlers:
   - TestCreateActionItemHandler: valid creation, empty task
   - TestToggleCompletedHandler: toggle on, toggle off
   - TestUpdateActionItemHandler: update task text, update assignee

5. internal/handlers/board_test.go -- Unit tests for board handlers:
   - TestEndRetroHandler: verify board gets archived and new board is created

6. internal/sse/hub_test.go -- Unit tests for SSE hub:
   - TestHubRegisterClient: client registers and receives events
   - TestHubBroadcast: event sent to correct team, not to other teams
   - TestHubUnregisterClient: client disconnects cleanly

7. internal/db/queries_test.go -- Integration tests (require Postgres):
   - Add a build tag or TestMain that skips if DATABASE_URL is not set
   - Create a test helper: func setupTestDB(t *testing.T) *pgxpool.Pool that connects using DATABASE_URL, runs migrations, and returns the pool. Use t.Cleanup to drop test data or use a transaction that rolls back.
   - TestCreateAndGetTeam: create team, retrieve by name, verify fields
   - TestBoardLifecycle: create board, archive it, verify archived boards list
   - TestThoughtCRUD: create, update, delete, get by board
   - TestActionItemCRUD: create, update, toggle complete, delete
   - TestIncrementHearts: verify heart count increases

8. internal/models/models_test.go -- Unit tests for any model methods or validation (if applicable).

For handler tests that need database access, define a minimal interface that the handlers accept, and create a mock implementation in the test file. This keeps handler unit tests fast and independent of Postgres. The integration tests in internal/db/ cover the real database behavior.

After writing all tests, run 'go test ./...' via the shell tool. If any tests fail due to compilation errors or incorrect assumptions about the code, fix the tests (not the application code -- that is for the review stage). If a test reveals a genuine bug in the application, document it in a file called TEST_NOTES.md but do NOT fix the application code."
	]

	review_fix [
		shape=box,
		label="Review and Fix",
		model="anthropic/claude-opus-4.6",
		max_retries=2,
		prompt="You are reviewing the entire RetroQuest Returns codebase for correctness and completeness. Read every Go source file, every template, every test file, the migration SQL, and the design documents.

Perform these checks systematically:

1. COMPILATION: Read all .go files. Check for:
   - Missing imports
   - Undefined variables or functions
   - Type mismatches
   - Incorrect function signatures
   - Missing interface implementations

2. ROUTE CONSISTENCY: Compare internal/server/server.go routes with internal/handlers/ implementations. Every registered route must have a corresponding handler. Every handler must be wired.

3. TEMPLATE CORRECTNESS: Check that:
   - Every template referenced in handlers exists in templates/
   - Template data fields match what handlers pass
   - htmx attributes (hx-post, hx-get, hx-delete, hx-put, hx-target, hx-swap) reference correct URLs
   - SSE event names in templates match what the backend sends

4. DATABASE: Check that:
   - All queries use parameterized inputs (no SQL injection)
   - Migration SQL matches the models in internal/models/
   - Foreign key references are correct

5. FEATURE COMPLETENESS: Compare against FEATURE_SPEC.md and DESIGN.md:
   - Is every Tier 1 feature implemented?
   - Are there any missing handlers or templates?

6. SECURITY: Check for:
   - Password hashing (bcrypt) on team creation
   - Auth middleware on all /team/* routes
   - CSRF considerations for htmx forms
   - No secrets hardcoded in source

7. TESTS: Run 'go test ./...' via the shell tool. If any tests fail:
   - Determine whether the failure is a bug in the application code or a bug in the test
   - Fix whichever is wrong
   - Re-run until all tests pass
   Also read TEST_NOTES.md if it exists -- the testing stage may have documented application bugs it found but did not fix.

Fix every issue you find. For each fix, edit the file directly. After fixing, do a final read-through of any files you changed to verify the fixes are correct.

Write a file called REVIEW_NOTES.md documenting what you found and fixed."
	]

	final_check [
		shape=box,
		label="Final Verification",
		model="anthropic/claude-opus-4.6",
		max_retries=2,
		goal_gate=true,
		prompt="You are performing the final verification of RetroQuest Returns. A previous review stage already found and fixed issues. Read REVIEW_NOTES.md to see what was addressed.

Do a focused check on these areas:

1. Read cmd/server/main.go and internal/server/server.go -- verify the server starts correctly, all routes are registered, middleware is applied.

2. Read every handler file in internal/handlers/ -- verify each handler:
   - Reads request data correctly
   - Calls the right database function
   - Returns the right template partial or redirect
   - Sends NOTIFY for real-time updates where appropriate

3. Read every template in templates/ -- verify:
   - base.html includes all CDN links (Tailwind, htmx, htmx-sse)
   - retro.html has correct SSE connection setup
   - All partials have correct htmx attributes
   - Responsive classes are present

4. Read internal/sse/hub.go -- verify SSE implementation:
   - Clients can connect and disconnect cleanly
   - Events are broadcast to correct team
   - Postgres LISTEN is set up

5. Check that go.mod lists all required dependencies (pgx, bcrypt, go-cmp).

6. Run 'go test ./...' via the shell tool. ALL tests must pass. If any fail, fix the issue (application code or test code, whichever is wrong) and re-run until green.

Fix any remaining issues you find. This is the last stage before the pipeline completes, so be thorough.

Update REVIEW_NOTES.md with any additional findings from this pass."
	]

	start -> analyze -> design -> scaffold -> backend -> frontend -> tests -> review_fix -> final_check -> exit
}
